snippet.textDisplay:
Australia is a biased country(most countries of consequence have some form of bias or other) with a passion to not to allow itself be called unfair. I remember when Australians of Indian descent were denied entry back into Australia from India for some Covid reason and at the same time, their mostly white cricketeers were allowed to come in. Only after a huge hue and cry in India did they relent. 

I do not think all Australians are like that, but something in the government has this tendency. I remember a trainer from Australia who had come to India in 90s was always critical of India, its culture, its weather, its cleanliness (which I agree needs correction), but his job was not to comment on it, just train and go. However he was very vocal and I heard he was beaten up by some people on another batch he was training. I totally do not support that, and hopefully the culprits were caught and punished. However that is my first first hand experience of an Australian. 

Although to be fair, first impressions are not necessarily true, but I looked at their behavior colored by the behavior of that person and I always felt that many of them were bit off. e.g. Sledging in Cricket etc..

I also have friends that claim they are some of the nicest people that they have ever experienced, I believe that could be true and so could the general image I was forced to build due to my experience. 

In this case, I am fine that they deported this tennis guy, and I think that is quire fair too, but there is a question if they would do the same to another guy if they were from Britain or US or New Zealand, I am not sure.

snippet.textDisplay:
All tennis fans are disappointed. Novak may very well be the best player in history and is a delight to watch. However, the world is facing a prolonged pandemic. Australia has faced this with strong protective measures. Novak handled his end of this affair poorly; he doesn't need to get vaxed, but he does have to follow the rules. He did not. Indeed, the investigation showed him to have been openly playing with children, unmasked, on the day he claims to have had a positive test. This sets a terrible example for the world. Sportsmen have a special obligation to set a positive example because young people look up to and are influenced by them. We need our heroes, but we need them to be worthy of emulation, and in this case Novak is not. 

HIs father has consistently set a poor example as a sportsman's parent. His claim that Australia has shot Novak 50 times in the chest is incendiary. The Serb government's behavior is also deplorable, making a big political issue out of another nation's public health policies, claiming that Australia has been "tainted." Perhaps the current leaders have forgotten such names as Slobodan Milošević and Radovan Karadžić. These are the kind of folks who taint a country's reputation.

If it is a public safety then they wouldn't grant him entrance in the first place. If the decison was based on scientific research the vaccination wouldn't be  mandatory but either negative PCR or quarantine, or both. Reason? Vaccinated ppl can still get and spread the virus (scientifically proved). If the logic and common sense were behind the decison they would realize that more than 1M people who got infected in Aus in only one moth (90%+ vaccinated) can't be compromised by someone whose "fault" is  - being not vaccinated. 

All this is written by a person who has got three shots, got infected, had alomost zero symptoms and who was persuading his family to do the same to protect THEMSELVES from getting sick.

So, it's an easy answer - pure politics and populism. Trying to not put more salt on the wounds of people of Australia who are living in a pretty restricted conditions, that are not imposed in any other developed country. Maybe they will feel better now for few days. Even that is enough for politicians before the elections.
